 social justice and biological conservation must go hand in hand. The protection of nature is a complex social enterprise, and much more a process of politics, and of human organization, than ecology. Although this political complexity is recognized by practitioners, it rarely enters into the problem analyses that inform conservation policy. Structured around conceptual chapters and supporting case studies that examine the politics of conservation in specific contexts, the book shows that pursuing social justice enhances biodiversity conservation rather than diminishing it, and that the fate of local peoples and that of conservation are completely intertwined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBiodiversity conservationxPolitical aspectszDeveloping countries. 0aBiodiversity conservationxSocial aspectszDeveloping countries. 0aProtected areasxPolitical aspectszDeveloping countries. 0aProtected areasxSocial aspectszDeveloping countries. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh1 aAgbo, Valentin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelsky, Jill M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenjamin, Charles E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrechin, Steven R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrechin, Steven R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuhat, Delma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorsey, Michael K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFortwangler, Crystal L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators